Since the shipment of 1000 items matches these proportions exactly, we calculate the number of items that have no defects ($n_{\text{good}}$).

$$
\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{good}} &= 1000 \times 0.54 \\
&= 540 \text{ items}
\end{aligned}
$$

First, we look at the initial draw. We are given that the probability of drawing a red marble is $\frac{6}{10}$. Since the sum of probabilities for all branches from a single point must equal 1, we can find the probability of drawing a blue marble using the **Complementary Probabilities** approach.

$$
\begin{aligned}
P(\text{Blue}) &= 1 - P(\text{Red}) \\
P(\text{Blue}) &= 1 - \frac{6}{10} \\
P(\text{Blue}) &= \frac{4}{10}
\end{aligned}
$$
